HEADER: Stanton & Zukoff (2015) - Prosodic effects of segmental correspondence
TITLE: Prosodic effects of segmental correspondence
AUTHORTITLE: Stanton & Zukoff (2015)
RAWAUTHORS: <a href="/lingbuzz/002703?_s=V7hdwuh0k7u6xEZy&amp;_k=SIhRl4JtogNFnZhj&amp;1">Juliet Stanton</a>, <a href="/lingbuzz/002703?_s=V7hdwuh0k7u6xEZy&amp;_k=SIhRl4JtogNFnZhj&amp;2">Sam Zukoff</a>
AUTHORS: Juliet Stanton, Sam Zukoff
LASTNAMES: Stanton, Zukoff
MONTH: September
YEAR: 2015
ABSTRACT: This paper investigates a class of misapplication effects arising in reduplication and copy-epenthesis, specifically those relating to the assignment of phonological properties related to prominence. We argue that extensions of Correspondence Theory (McCarthy & Prince 1995) can explain these effects, given a grammar that contains: (1) a correspondence relation between surface segments, arising when multiple output segments correspond to a single input segment (also Struijke 2000, McCarthy 2002); and (2) faithfulness constraints requiring identity among these correspondents for suprasegmental properties. We show that a grammar with these properties provides a unified account of a range of prosodic misapplication effects.
